### 2. Start Problem Solving Habit (Most Important Skill After Language)

**Why first year?**  
Because DSA is 60–80% of placement coding rounds.  
Start early = less pressure later.

**Platforms (free & best in 2026):**  
- CodeChef → best for absolute beginners (starters contests)  
- LeetCode → king for placements (explore, blind 75, company tags)  
- GeeksforGeeks → practice section + articles  
- HackerRank → good basics  
- CodeStudio (Coding Ninjas) → structured paths  

**Weekly progression plan (follow strictly):**

Weeks 1–4  
- Pattern printing (star pyramids, number patterns, alphabet patterns) – 15–20 problems  
- Basic math: prime check, factorial, GCD, LCM, sum of digits, reverse number  

Weeks 5–8  
- Arrays basics: sum, max/min, second max, reverse array, rotate array (left/right by k)  
- Linear search, count occurrences  

Weeks 9–12  
- Strings: reverse string, palindrome check, remove duplicates, anagram check  
- Count frequency of characters  

Weeks 13–16  
- 2D arrays: spiral traversal, matrix rotation 90°, search in sorted matrix  
- Basic bit manipulation: set bit, unset bit, count set bits  

Weeks 17–20  
- Simple recursion: factorial, fibonacci, sum of digits recursive  
- Subarray sum problems (easy)  

**Rules for problem solving:**  
- Never copy code directly  
- Struggle 15–30 minutes → read hint → struggle again → see editorial/solution  
- Write clean code with comments  
- Note time & space complexity  
- Revise every solved problem after 1 week  
- Target: **minimum 3–5 problems per week** (consistency > quantity)

### 3. Understand How Computers Actually Work (CSE Student Must-Know)

You are not just a coder – you are an engineer. Understand systems.

**Topics to cover (simple explanations):**

- What is a computer? Input → Process → Output → Storage  
- Binary system (0 & 1) – why everything is binary  
- Bits, bytes, KB, MB, GB, TB  
- RAM vs ROM vs Cache vs Hard disk/SSD  
- CPU components: ALU, CU, Registers  
- How code runs: source code → compiler/interpreter → machine code  
- Compilation vs Interpretation (C++ vs Python)  
- Stack memory vs Heap memory (where variables live)  
- What happens when you declare int x = 5;?  
- Operating System basics: process, thread, multitasking  
- File system, paths (absolute vs relative)  
- What is Git & version control? Why companies force it  

**Resources (short & clear):**  
- Neso Academy – Computer Fundamentals playlist  
- Apna College – "How Computer Works" series  
- GeeksforGeeks – Operating System & Computer Organization sections  
- Crash Course Computer Science (YouTube – English, 10–15 min videos)

