## 🧱 Phase 2 – Core Engineering Level-Up (Months 6–12 | End of First Year)

Now shift to serious mode.

### 5. Data Structures & Algorithms Deep Dive – The Placement King

**Order to learn (do not skip):**

Months 6–7  
- Advanced Arrays: Kadane’s algorithm, sliding window, two pointers  
- Strings deep: KMP basics, longest palindromic substring intro  
- Searching: Binary search variants (first/last occurrence, floor/ceil)  
- Sorting deep: Merge sort, Quick sort understanding + when to use  

Months 8–9  
- Linked List: reverse, detect cycle, middle, merge two sorted, remove nth from end  
- Stack: next greater element, parentheses validation, largest rectangle histogram intro  
- Queue: circular queue, deque basics  

Months 10–11  
- Recursion deep: subsets, permutations, combination sum, backtracking basics  
- Binary Trees: traversal (pre/in/post/level), height, diameter, mirror, LCA intro  

Months 11–12  
- Hashing: map vs unordered_map, collision handling basics  
- Greedy intro: activity selection, fractional knapsack  
- Time & Space Complexity: Big O, Omega, Theta – analyze every problem  

**Target numbers by end of first year:**  
- 200–300 problems solved  
- Breakdown: 80–100 easy + 120–180 medium  
- Use: Striver SDE Sheet (180–200 most important) + Love Babbar 450 list (select topics)  

**Best practice method:**  
- Topic → watch 1 explanation video (Striver / takeUforward) → solve 10–15 problems on that topic → revise after 7 days

### 6. Git & GitHub Mastery (Your Public Resume)

**Must-know commands with real use:**

git init → start new repo  
git add . → stage all changes  
git commit -m "Added calculator project" → save changes  
git remote add origin https://github.com/yourusername/repo.git  
git push -u origin main → upload to GitHub  

git clone https://github.com/... → download someone’s repo  
git status → see what changed  
git log → see commit history  
git branch feature-login → create branch  
git checkout feature-login → switch branch  
git merge feature-login → merge to main  
git pull origin main → update local from remote  

**Pro habits:**  
- Commit daily: small messages like "Fixed input bug in quiz app"  
- Write good README.md for every project (purpose, features, how to run, screenshots)  
- Use .gitignore (ignore unnecessary files like .exe, .o)  
- Pin 4–6 best repos on GitHub profile  

### 7. Build Real Projects (Proof You Can Code)

**Rule:** Finish at least 1 project every 2–3 months.  
**Do NOT** watch full tutorial and copy – understand + modify + add your features.

**First-year project ideas (start simple → add complexity):**

Project 1 (Month 2–3) – Console Calculator (C++)  
- Add, subtract, multiply, divide  
- Power, square root, modulo  
- Error handling (divide by zero)  
- History of last 5 calculations  

Project 2 (Month 4–5) – To-Do List Manager  
- Add task, delete task, mark complete  
- Show all / pending / completed  
- Save to file (file handling)  
- Priority levels  

Project 3 (Month 6–7) – Number Guessing + Quiz Game  
- Computer thinks number → user guesses  
- Score system  
- MCQ quiz (5–10 questions) with timer  
- Save high score  

Project 4 (Month 8–9) – Student Record System  
- Add student (name, roll, marks)  
- Delete, update, search by roll/name  
- Show all sorted by marks  
- Use structures/classes  

Project 5 (Month 10–12) – Basic Portfolio Website  
- HTML + CSS  
- Home, About, Skills, Projects, Contact sections  
- Responsive (mobile friendly)  
- Host on GitHub Pages  

**Later add-ons for all projects:**  
- GUI using Tkinter (Python) or basic graphics.h (C++)  
- Database (text file → later SQLite)  
- Upload to GitHub + deploy if web  

## 🌐 Phase 3 – Choose Your Direction (By End of First Year)

Pick **ONE** path and go deep – do not do everything.

**Path A: Web Development** (highest job availability)  
- Month 12–18: HTML5, CSS3, Flexbox, Grid, Responsive design, JavaScript basics (DOM, events, fetch)  
- Build: 5–7 websites (portfolio, e-commerce landing, blog, admin dashboard)  
- Later: React.js, Tailwind, Next.js  

**Path B: Backend / Full-Stack**  
- Node.js + Express  
- REST API concepts (GET, POST, PUT, DELETE)  
- MongoDB / MySQL basics  
- JWT authentication  
- Build: Todo API, Blog API, E-commerce backend  

**Path C: Competitive Programming** (if you love pure logic)  
- Codeforces / AtCoder / CodeChef daily  
- Learn advanced STL, binary search tricks, DP basics  
- Target rating: Specialist (1400+) by end 2nd year  

**Path D: AI / Data / ML** (hot but needs maths + patience)  
- Python deep + NumPy, Pandas, Matplotlib  
- Basic ML: linear regression, classification  
- Later: TensorFlow / PyTorch intro  

